#limitation(title: [NIH “Effort Preference” Controversy: Limitations on Both Sides])[
The debate over the Walitt et al.\ “effort preference” framing illustrates epistemic limitations in both the original study and its critiques. The original study's n=17 sample, single-day CPET design, and use of a task (EEfRT) not validated for physically impaired populations limit the strength of its conclusions. However, the Kirvin-Quamme et al.\ reanalysis @kirvinquamme2025effort, while methodologically sound, uses the same small dataset; a definitive resolution requires larger studies with tasks calibrated to participants' physical capacity. Neither side has established whether the observed motor behavior differences reflect conscious preference, unconscious neural computation, or simple physical inability—these are empirically distinguishable but have not been distinguished.
]
